The proposed roadmap to recycle toxic lead and valuable glass substrates from perovskite solar modules is sketched in Fig. 1. After the delamination of encapsulated perovskite solar modules, the lead in perovskite layer is dissolved by organic solvent, such as dimethylformamide (DMF). Lead ions are first adsorbed by a lead adsorbent to fully remove lead in the organic solvent, and then are released to clean solvent, followed by a precipitation to PbI2 for reuse. In this study, we chose carboxylic acid cation-exchange resin as adsorbent to recycle lead in decommissioned perovskite solar modules. The lead-adsorption process and lead-release process on resins are based on ion exchange between H+ ions and Pb2+ ions:12R−COOH+Pb2+↔R−COO2Pb+2H+\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
